# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: awk-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:awk-lang/awk] The AWK language is a data-driven scripting language consisting of a set of actions to be taken against streams of textual data – either run directly on files or used as part of a pipeline – for purposes of extracting or transforming text, such as producing formatted reports.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The language extensively uses the string datatype, associative arrays (that is, arrays indexed by key strings), and regular expressions.
[src:awk-lang/awk] While AWK has a limited intended application domain and was especially designed to support one-liner programs, the language is Turing-complete, and even the early Bell Labs users of AWK often wrote well-structured large AWK programs.
[src:awk-lang/awk] AWK was created at Bell Labs in the 1970s, and its name is derived from the surnames of its authors: Alfred Aho (author of egrep), Peter Weinberger (who worked on tiny relational databases), and Brian Kernighan.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The acronym is pronounced the same as the name of the bird species auk, which is illustrated on the cover of *The AWK Programming Language*.
[src:awk-lang/awk] According to Brian Kernighan, one of the goals of AWK was to have a tool that would easily manipulate both numbers and strings.
[src:awk-lang/awk] AWK was also inspired by Marc Rochkind's programming language that was used to search for patterns in input data, and was implemented using yacc.
[src:awk-lang/awk] As one of the early tools to appear in Version 7 Unix, AWK added computational features to a Unix pipeline besides the Bourne shell, the only scripting language available in a standard Unix environment.
[src:awk-lang/awk] It is one of the mandatory utilities of the Single UNIX Specification, and is required by the Linux Standard Base specification.
[src:awk-lang/awk] In 1983, AWK was one of several UNIX tools available for Charles River Data Systems' UNOS operating system under Bell Laboratories license.
[src:awk-lang/awk] AWK was significantly revised and expanded in 1985–88, resulting in the GNU AWK implementation written by Paul Rubin, Jay Fenlason, and Richard Stallman, released in 1988.
[src:awk-lang/awk] GNU AWK may be the most widely deployed version because it is included with GNU-based Linux packages.
[src:awk-lang/awk] GNU AWK has been maintained solely by Arnold Robbins since 1994.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Brian Kernighan's nawk (New AWK) source was first released in 1993 unpublicized, and publicly since the late 1990s; many BSD systems use it to avoid the GPL license.
[src:awk-lang/awk] They share the line-oriented, data-driven paradigm, and are particularly suited to writing one-liner programs, due to the implicit main loop and current line variables.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The power and terseness of early AWK programs – notably the powerful regular expression handling and conciseness due to implicit variables, which facilitate one-liners – together with the limitations of AWK at the time, were important inspirations for the Perl language (1987).
[src:awk-lang/awk] In the 1990s, Perl became very popular, competing with AWK in the niche of Unix text-processing languages.
[src:awk-lang/awk] where *condition* is typically an expression and *action* is a series of commands.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The input is split into records, where by default records are separated by newline characters so that the input is split into lines.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The program tests each record against each of the conditions in turn, and executes the *action* for each expression that is true.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Either the condition or the action may be omitted.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The condition defaults to matching every record.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The default action is to print the record.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This is the same pattern-action structure as sed.
[src:awk-lang/awk] In addition to normal arithmetic and logical operators, AWK expressions include the tilde operator, `~`, which matches a regular expression against a string.
[src:awk-lang/awk] As handy syntactic sugar, */regexp/* without using the tilde operator matches against the current record; this syntax derives from sed, which in turn inherited it from the ed editor, where `/` is used for searching.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This syntax of using slashes as delimiters for regular expressions was subsequently adopted by Perl and ECMAScript, and is now common.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The tilde operator was also adopted by Perl.
[src:awk-lang/awk] AWK commands are the statements that are substituted for *action* in the examples above.
[src:awk-lang/awk] AWK commands can include function calls, variable assignments, calculations, or any combination thereof.
[src:awk-lang/awk] AWK contains built-in support for many functions; many more are provided by the various flavors of AWK.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Also, some flavors support the inclusion of dynamically linked libraries, which can also provide more functions.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The *print* command is used to output text.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The output text is always terminated with a predefined string called the output record separator (ORS) whose default value is a newline.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This displays the contents of the current record.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Although these fields (*$X*) may bear resemblance to variables (the $ symbol indicates variables in the usual Unix shells and in Perl), they actually refer to the fields of the current record.
[src:awk-lang/awk] A special case, *$0*, refers to the entire record.
[src:awk-lang/awk] In fact, the commands "`print`" and "`print $0`" are identical in functionality.
[src:awk-lang/awk] AWK's built-in variables include the field variables: $1, $2, $3, and so on ($0 represents the entire record).
[src:awk-lang/awk] They hold the text or values in the individual text-fields in a record.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The operators `+` `-` `*` `/` `^` `%` represent addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, exponentiation, and remainder, respectively.
[src:awk-lang/awk] For division and remainder, the same operators apply to both integer and floating point divisions.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The `int( dividend / divisor )` approach may lead to edge cases that round incorrectly.
[src:awk-lang/awk] For string concatenation, simply place two variables (or string constants) next to each other.
[src:awk-lang/awk] It is optional to use a space in between if string constants are involved, but two variable names placed adjacent to each other require a space in between.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Unlike Unix shells or other languages like Perl, the sigil-less single underscore variable name (`_`) is neither reserved nor special, and can be freely utilized by the user.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Double quotes (`"..."`), and only double quotes, delimit string constants.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Statements and / or expressions need not end with semicolons.
[src:awk-lang/awk] In fact, the only place where the semi-colon `;` is absolutely unavoidable is the 3-argument variant of the `for ()` loop that largely resembles its counterpart in `C/C++` .
[src:awk-lang/awk] All non-array arguments to functions are passed "by-value", making them freely mutable by the function while guaranteeing being side-effect free to the function's upstream caller.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Unlike Python, all augmented assignments in `awk` such as `+=` `-=` `*=` `/=` `^=` `%=` are expressions.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This allows for effective unlimited-length chaining.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Finally, comments can be added to programs by using `#` as the first character on a line, or behind a command or sequence of commands.
[src:awk-lang/awk] In a format similar to C, function definitions consist of the keyword `function`, the function name, argument names and the function body.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Functions can have variables that are in the local scope.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The names of these are added to the end of the argument list, though values for these should be omitted when calling the function.
[src:awk-lang/awk] It is convention to add some whitespace in the argument list before the local variables, to indicate where the parameters end and the local variables begin.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Print all lines longer than 80 characters.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The default action is to print the current line.
[src:awk-lang/awk] As there is no pattern for the first line of the program, every line of input matches by default, so the increment actions are executed for every line.
[src:awk-lang/awk] `words += NF` is shorthand for `words = words + NF`.
[src:awk-lang/awk] `s` is incremented by the numeric value of `$NF`, which is the last word on the line as defined by AWK's field separator (by default, white-space).
[src:awk-lang/awk] `NF` is the number of fields in the current line, e.g.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Since `$4` is the value of the fourth field, `$NF` is the value of the last field in the line regardless of how many fields this line has, or whether it has more or fewer fields than surrounding lines.
[src:awk-lang/awk] `$` is actually a unary operator with the highest operator precedence.
[src:awk-lang/awk] At the end of the input, the `END` pattern matches, so `s` is printed.
[src:awk-lang/awk] However, since there may have been no lines of input at all, in which case no value has ever been assigned to `s`, `s` will be an empty string by default.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Adding zero to a variable is an AWK idiom for coercing it from a string to a numeric value.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This results from AWK's arithmetic operators, like addition, implicitly casting their operands to numbers before computation as required.
[src:awk-lang/awk] (Similarly, concatenating a variable with an empty string coerces from a number to a string, e.g., `s ""`.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Note, there is no operator to concatenate strings, they are just placed adjacently.) On an empty input, the coercion in `{ print s + 0 }` causes the program to print `0`, whereas with just the action `{ print s }`, an empty line would be printed.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The action statement prints each line numbered.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The printf function emulates the standard C printf and works similarly to the print command described above.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The pattern to match, however, works as follows: *NR* is the number of records, typically lines of input, AWK has so far read, i.e. the current line number, starting at 1 for the first line of input.
[src:awk-lang/awk] *NR % 4 == 1* is true for the 1st, 5th, 9th, etc., lines of input.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Likewise, *NR % 4 == 3* is true for the 3rd, 7th, 11th, etc., lines of input.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The range pattern is false until the first part matches, on line 1, and then remains true up to and including when the second part matches, on line 3.
[src:awk-lang/awk] It then stays false until the first part matches again on line 5.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Thus, the program prints lines 1,2,3, skips line 4, and then 5,6,7, and so on.
[src:awk-lang/awk] For each line, it prints the line number (on a 6 character-wide field) and then the line contents.
[src:awk-lang/awk] As a special case, when the first part of a range pattern is constantly true, e.g.
[src:awk-lang/awk] *1*, the range will start at the beginning of the input.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Similarly, if the second part is constantly false, e.g.
[src:awk-lang/awk] *0*, the range will continue until the end of input.
[src:awk-lang/awk] prints lines of input from the first line matching the regular expression *^--cut here--$*, that is, a line containing only the phrase "--cut here--", to the end.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The BEGIN block sets the field separator to any sequence of non-alphabetic characters.
[src:awk-lang/awk] After that, we get to a bare action, which performs the action on every input line.
[src:awk-lang/awk] In this case, for every field on the line, we add one to the number of times that word, first converted to lowercase, appears.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Finally, in the END block, we print the words with their frequencies.
[src:awk-lang/awk] creates a loop that goes through the array *words*, setting *i* to each *subscript* of the array.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This is different from most languages, where such a loop goes through each *value* in the array.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The loop thus prints out each word followed by its frequency count.
[src:awk-lang/awk] `tolower` was an addition to the One True awk (see below) made after the book was published.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This program can be represented in several ways.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The first one uses the Bourne shell to make a shell script that does everything.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The `$pattern` in the awk command is not protected by single quotes so that the shell does expand the variable but it needs to be put in double quotes to properly handle patterns containing spaces.
[src:awk-lang/awk] A pattern by itself in the usual way checks to see if the whole line (`$0`) matches.
[src:awk-lang/awk] `FILENAME` contains the current filename. awk has no explicit concatenation operator; two adjacent strings concatenate them.
[src:awk-lang/awk] `$0` expands to the original unchanged input line.
[src:awk-lang/awk] There are alternate ways of writing this.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This is a shell script that uses `ENVIRON`, an array introduced in a newer version of the One True awk after the book was published.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The subscript of `ENVIRON` is the name of an environment variable; its result is the variable's value.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This is like the getenv function in various standard libraries and POSIX.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The shell script makes an environment variable `pattern` containing the first argument, then drops that argument and has awk look for the pattern in each file.
[src:awk-lang/awk] `~` checks to see if its left operand matches its right operand; `!~` is its inverse.
[src:awk-lang/awk] A regular expression is just a string and can be stored in variables.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Or You can use the *-v var=value* command line option (e.g.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The `BEGIN` is necessary not only to extract the first argument, but also to prevent it from being interpreted as a filename after the `BEGIN` block ends.
[src:awk-lang/awk] `ARGC`, the number of arguments, is always guaranteed to be ≥1, as `ARGV[0]` is the name of the command that executed the script, most often the string `"awk"`.
[src:awk-lang/awk] `#` initiates a comment that expands to the end of the line.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Note the `if` block. awk only checks to see if it should read from standard input before it runs the command.
[src:awk-lang/awk] only works because the fact that there are no filenames is only checked before `prog` is run!
[src:awk-lang/awk] If you explicitly set `ARGC` to 1 so that there are no arguments, awk will simply quit because it feels there are no more input files.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Therefore, you need to explicitly say to read from standard input with the special filename `-`.
[src:awk-lang/awk] On Unix-like operating systems self-contained AWK scripts can be constructed using the shebang syntax.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The `-f` tells awk that the argument that follows is the file to read the AWK program from, which is the same flag that is used in sed.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Since they are often used for one-liners, both these programs default to executing a program given as a command-line argument, rather than a separate file.
[src:awk-lang/awk] AWK was originally written in 1977 and distributed with Version 7 Unix.
[src:awk-lang/awk] In 1985 its authors started expanding the language, most significantly by adding user-defined functions.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The language is described in the book *The AWK Programming Language*, published 1988, and its implementation was made available in releases of UNIX System V.
[src:awk-lang/awk] To avoid confusion with the incompatible older version, this version was sometimes called "new awk" or *nawk*.
[src:awk-lang/awk] This implementation was released under a free software license in 1996 and is still maintained by Brian Kernighan (see external links below).
[src:awk-lang/awk] Old versions of Unix, such as UNIX/32V, included `awkcc`, which converted AWK to C.
[src:awk-lang/awk] Kernighan wrote a program to turn awk into C++; its state is not known.
[src:awk-lang/awk] The gawk manual has a list of more AWK implementations.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This file documents `awk`, a program that you can use to select particular records in a file and perform operations upon them.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This is Edition 5.4 of *GAWK: Effective AWK Programming: A User’s Guide for GNU Awk*, for the 5.4.0 (or later) version of the GNU implementation of AWK.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] A copy of the license is included in the section entitled “GNU Free Documentation License”.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] We were introduced in 1990 by circumstances—and our favorite programming language, AWK.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The circumstances started a couple of years earlier.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] I was working at a new job and noticed an unplugged Unix computer sitting in the corner.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] No one knew how to use it, and neither did I.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] However, a couple of days later, it was running, and I was `root` and the one-and-only user.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] That day, I began the transition from statistician to Unix programmer.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] On one of many trips to the library or bookstore in search of books on Unix, I found the gray AWK book, a.k.a.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Weinberger’s *The AWK Programming Language* (Addison-Wesley, 1988).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] `awk`’s simple programming paradigm—find a pattern in the input and then perform an action—often reduced complex or tedious data manipulations to a few lines of code.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] I was excited to try my hand at programming in AWK.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Alas, the `awk` on my computer was a limited version of the language described in the gray book.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] I discovered that my computer had “old `awk`” and the book described “new `awk`.” I learned that this was typical; the old version refused to step aside or relinquish its name.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] If a system had a new `awk`, it was invariably called `nawk`, and few systems had it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The best way to get a new `awk` was to `ftp` the source code for `gawk` from `prep.ai.mit.edu`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] `gawk` was a version of new `awk` written by David Trueman and Arnold, and available under the GNU General Public License.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] (Incidentally, it’s no longer difficult to find a new `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] My Unix system started out unplugged from the wall; it certainly was not plugged into a network.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] So, oblivious to the existence of `gawk` and the Unix community in general, and desiring a new `awk`, I wrote my own, called `mawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Before I was finished, I knew about `gawk`, but it was too late to stop, so I eventually posted to a `comp.sources` newsgroup.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] A few days after my posting, I got a friendly email from Arnold introducing himself.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] He suggested we share design and algorithms and attached a draft of the POSIX standard so that I could update `mawk` to support language extensions added after publication of *The AWK Programming Language*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Frankly, if our roles had been reversed, I would not have been so open and we probably would have never met.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] He is an AWK expert’s AWK expert and a genuinely nice person.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Arnold contributes significant amounts of his expertise and time to the Free Software Foundation.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This book is the `gawk` reference manual, but at its core it is a book about AWK programming that will appeal to a wide audience.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] It is a definitive reference to the AWK language as defined by the 1987 Bell Laboratories release and codified in the 1992 POSIX Utilities standard.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] On the other hand, the novice AWK programmer can study a wealth of practical programs that emphasize the power of AWK’s basic idioms: data-driven control flow, pattern matching with regular expressions, and associative arrays.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Those looking for something new can try out `gawk`’s interface to network protocols via special /inet files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The programs in this book make clear that an AWK program is typically much smaller and faster to develop than a counterpart written in C.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Consequently, there is often a payoff to prototyping an algorithm or design in AWK to get it running quickly and expose problems early.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Often, the interpreted performance is adequate and the AWK prototype becomes the product.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The new `pgawk` (profiling `gawk`), produces program execution counts.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] I recently experimented with an algorithm that for *n* lines of input, exhibited ~ C n^2 performance, while theory predicted ~ C n log n behavior.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] A few minutes poring over the awkprof.out profile pinpointed the problem to a single line of code.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] `pgawk` is a welcome addition to my programmer’s toolbox.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Arnold has distilled over a decade of experience writing and using AWK programs, and developing `gawk`, into this book.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] If you use AWK or want to learn how, then read this book.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Thirteen years ago I wrote: “If you use AWK or want to learn how, then read this book.” True then, and still true today.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Learning to use a programming language is about more than mastering the syntax.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] One needs to acquire an understanding of how to use the features of the language to solve practical programming problems.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] A focus of this book is many examples that show how to use AWK.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Our computers are much faster and have more memory.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Consequently, speed and storage inefficiencies of a high-level language matter less.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Prototyping in AWK and then rewriting in C for performance reasons happens less, because more often the prototype is fast enough.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Of course, there are computing operations that are best done in C or C++.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] With `gawk` 4.1 and later, you do not have to choose between writing your program in AWK or in C/C++.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] You can write most of your program in AWK and the aspects that require C/C++ capabilities can be written in C/C++, and then the pieces glued together when the `gawk` module loads the C/C++ module as a dynamic plug-in.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Writing Extensions for `gawk`, has all the details, and, as expected, many examples to help you learn the ins and outs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] I enjoy programming in AWK and had fun (re)reading this book.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Several kinds of tasks occur repeatedly when working with text files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] You might want to extract certain lines and discard the rest.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Or you may need to make changes wherever certain patterns appear, but leave the rest of the file alone.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The `awk` utility interprets a special-purpose programming language that makes it easy to handle simple data-reformatting jobs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The GNU implementation of `awk` is called `gawk`; if you invoke it with the proper options or environment variables, it is fully compatible with the POSIX1 specification of the `awk` language and with the Unix version of `awk` maintained by Brian Kernighan.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This means that all properly written `awk` programs should work with `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] So most of the time, we don’t distinguish between `gawk` and other `awk` implementations.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This Web page teaches you about the `awk` language and how you can use it effectively.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] You should already be familiar with basic system commands, such as `cat` and `ls`,2 as well as basic shell facilities, such as input/output (I/O) redirection and pipes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Implementations of the `awk` language are available for many different computing environments.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This Web page, while describing the `awk` language in general, also describes the particular implementation of `awk` called `gawk` (which stands for “GNU `awk`”).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] `gawk` runs on a broad range of Unix systems, ranging from Intel-architecture PC-based computers up through large-scale systems.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The name `awk` comes from the initials of its designers: Alfred V.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The original version of `awk` was written in 1977 at AT&T Bell Laboratories.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] In 1985, a new version made the programming language more powerful, introducing user-defined functions, multiple input streams, and computed regular expressions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This new version became widely available with Unix System V Release 3.1 (1987).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The version in System V Release 4 (1989) added some new features and cleaned up the behavior in some of the “dark corners” of the language.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The specification for `awk` in the POSIX Command Language and Utilities standard further clarified the language.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Both the `gawk` designers and the original `awk` designers at Bell Laboratories provided feedback for the POSIX specification.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Jay Fenlason completed it, with advice from Richard Stallman.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] John Woods contributed parts of the code as well.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] In 1988 and 1989, David Trueman, with help from me, thoroughly reworked `gawk` for compatibility with the newer `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Circa 1994, I became the primary maintainer.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Current development focuses on bug fixes, performance improvements, standards compliance, and, occasionally, new features.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] In May 1997, Jürgen Kahrs felt the need for network access from `awk`, and with a little help from me, set about adding features to do this for `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] At that time, he also wrote the bulk of *TCP/IP Internetworking with `gawk`* (a separate document, available as part of the `gawk` distribution).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] His code finally became part of the main `gawk` distribution with `gawk` version 3.1.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] John Haque rewrote the `gawk` internals, in the process providing an `awk`-level debugger.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This version became available as `gawk` version 4.0 in 2011.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] See Major Contributors to `gawk` for a full list of those who have made important contributions to `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The `awk` language has evolved over the years.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Full details are provided in The Evolution of the `awk` Language.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] In this case, you should find a version of new `awk`, or just install `gawk`!
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Throughout this Web page, whenever we refer to a language feature that should be available in any complete implementation of POSIX `awk`, we simply use the term `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] When referring to a feature that is specific to the GNU implementation, we use the term `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The term `awk` refers to a particular program as well as to the language you use to tell this program what to do.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] When we need to be careful, we call the language “the `awk` language,” and the program “the `awk` utility.” This Web page explains both how to write programs in the `awk` language and how to run the `awk` utility.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The term “`awk` program” refers to a program written by you in the `awk` programming language.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Primarily, this Web page explains the features of `awk` as defined in the POSIX standard.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] It does so in the context of the `gawk` implementation.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] While doing so, it also attempts to describe important differences between `gawk` and other `awk` implementations.5 Finally, it notes any `gawk` features that are not in the POSIX standard for `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This Web page has the difficult task of being both a tutorial and a reference.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] If you are a novice, feel free to skip over details that seem too complex.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] You should also ignore the many cross-references; they are for the expert user and for the Info and HTML versions of the Web page.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] There are sidebars scattered throughout the Web page.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] They add a more complete explanation of points that are relevant, but not likely to be of interest on first reading.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Most of the time, the examples use complete `awk` programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Some of the more advanced sections show only the part of the `awk` program that illustrates the concept being described.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Although this Web page is aimed principally at people who have not been exposed to `awk`, there is a lot of information here that even the `awk` expert should find useful.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] In particular, the description of POSIX `awk` and the example programs in A Library of `awk` Functions, and in Practical `awk` Programs, should be of interest.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This Web page is written in Texinfo, the GNU documentation formatting language.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] A single Texinfo source file is used to produce both the printed and online versions of the documentation.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Because of this, the typographical conventions are slightly different than in other books you may have read.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Examples you would type at the command line are preceded by the common shell primary and secondary prompts, ‘$’ and ‘>’, respectively.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Output from the command is preceded by the glyph “-|”.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This typically represents the command’s standard output.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Error messages and other output on the command’s standard error are preceded by the glyph “error→”.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] In the text, almost anything related to programming, such as command names, variable and function names, and string, numeric and regexp constants appear in `this font`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Code fragments appear in the same font and quoted, ‘like this’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Things that are replaced by the user or programmer appear in *this font*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] File names are indicated like this: /path/to/ourfile.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Some things are emphasized *like this*, and if a point needs to be made strongly, it is done **like this**.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The first occurrence of a new term is usually its *definition* and appears in the same font as the previous occurrence of “definition” in this sentence.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Characters that you type at the keyboard look like this.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] In particular, there are special characters called “control characters.” These are characters that you type by holding down both the CONTROL key and another key, at the same time.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] For example, a Ctrl-d is typed by first pressing and holding the CONTROL key, next pressing the d key, and finally releasing both keys.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Until the POSIX standard (and *GAWK: Effective AWK Programming*), many features of `awk` were either poorly documented or not documented at all.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] But, as noted by the opening quote, any coverage of dark corners is by definition incomplete.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The Free Software Foundation (FSF) is a nonprofit organization dedicated to the production and distribution of freely distributable software.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Stallman, the author of the original Emacs editor.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] GNU Emacs is the most widely used version of Emacs today.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The GNU6 Project is an ongoing effort on the part of the Free Software Foundation to create a complete, freely distributable, POSIX-compliant computing environment.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The FSF uses the GNU General Public License (GPL) to ensure that its software’s source code is always available to the end user.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] A copy of the GPL is included in this Web page for your reference (see GNU General Public License).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The GPL applies to the C language source code for `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] To find out more about the FSF and the GNU Project online, see the GNU Project’s home page.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This Web page may also be read from GNU’s website.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] A shell, an editor (Emacs), highly portable optimizing C, C++, and Objective-C compilers, a symbolic debugger and dozens of large and small utilities (such as `gawk`), have all been completed and are freely available.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The GNU operating system kernel (the HURD), has been released but remains in an early stage of development.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Until the GNU operating system is more fully developed, you should consider using GNU/Linux, a freely distributable, Unix-like operating system for Intel, Power Architecture, Sun SPARC, IBM S/390, and other systems.7 Many GNU/Linux distributions are available for download from the Internet.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The Web page you are reading is actually free—at least, the information in it is free to anyone.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The machine-readable source code for the Web page comes with `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The Web page itself has gone through multiple previous editions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Paul Rubin wrote the very first draft of *The GAWK Manual*; it was around 40 pages long.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Diane Close and Richard Stallman improved it, yielding a version that was around 90 pages and barely described the original, “old” version of `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] I started working with that version in the fall of 1988.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] As work on it progressed, the FSF published several preliminary versions (numbered 0.*x*).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The FSF published the first two editions under the title *The GNU Awk User’s Guide*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This edition maintains the basic structure of the previous editions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] For FSF edition 4.0, the content was thoroughly reviewed and updated.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] All references to `gawk` versions prior to 4.0 were removed.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Of significant note for that edition was the addition of Debugging `awk` Programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] For FSF edition 5.0, the content has been reorganized into parts, and the major new additions are Arithmetic and Arbitrary-Precision Arithmetic with `gawk`, and Writing Extensions for `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] This Web page will undoubtedly continue to evolve.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] If you find an error in the Web page, please report it!
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] See Reporting Problems and Bugs for information on submitting problem reports electronically.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] As the maintainer of GNU `awk`, I once thought that I would be able to manage a collection of publicly available `awk` programs and I even solicited contributions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Making things available on the Internet helps keep the `gawk` distribution down to manageable size.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] The initial collection of material, such as it is, is still available at ftp://ftp.freefriends.org/arnold/Awkstuff.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] In the hopes of doing something broader, I acquired the `awklang.org` domain.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Late in 2017, a volunteer took on the task of managing it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] If you have written an interesting `awk` program that you would like to share with the rest of the world, please see http://www.awklang.org and use the “Contact” link.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] If you have written a `gawk` extension, please see The `gawkextlib` Project.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p01] Stallman, for his vision of a better world and for his courage in founding the FSF and starting the GNU Project.
