[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The basic function of `awk` is to search files for lines (or other units of text) that contain certain patterns.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] When a line matches one of the patterns, `awk` performs specified actions on that line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] `awk` continues to process input lines in this way until it reaches the end of the input files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Programs in `awk` are different from programs in most other languages, because `awk` programs are *data driven* (i.e., you describe the data you want to work with and then what to do when you find it).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Most other languages are *procedural*; you have to describe, in great detail, every step the program should take.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] When working with procedural languages, it is usually much harder to clearly describe the data your program will process.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] For this reason, `awk` programs are often refreshingly easy to read and write.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] When you run `awk`, you specify an `awk` *program* that tells `awk` what to do.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The program consists of a series of *rules* (it may also contain *function definitions*, an advanced feature that we will ignore for now; see User-Defined Functions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Each rule specifies one pattern to search for and one action to perform upon finding the pattern.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Syntactically, a rule consists of a *pattern* followed by an *action*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The action is enclosed in braces to separate it from the pattern.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] There are several ways to run an `awk` program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This section discusses both mechanisms, along with several variations of each.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Once you are familiar with `awk`, you will often type in simple programs the moment you want to use them.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] where *program* consists of a series of patterns and actions, as described earlier.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This command format instructs the *shell*, or command interpreter, to start `awk` and use the *program* to process records in the input file(s).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] There are single quotes around *program* so the shell won’t interpret any `awk` characters as special shell characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The quotes also cause the shell to treat all of *program* as a single argument for `awk`, and allow *program* to be more than one line long.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This format is also useful for running short or medium-sized `awk` programs from shell scripts, because it avoids the need for a separate file for the `awk` program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] A self-contained shell script is more reliable because there are no other files to misplace.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Later in this chapter, in Some Simple Examples, we’ll see examples of several short, self-contained programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] You can also run `awk` without any input files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] `awk` applies the *program* to the *standard input*, which usually means whatever you type on the keyboard.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This continues until you indicate end-of-file by typing Ctrl-d.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] `awk` executes statements associated with `BEGIN` before reading any input.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If there are no other statements in your program, as is the case here, `awk` just stops, instead of trying to read input it doesn’t know how to process.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The ‘\47’ is a magic way (explained later) of getting a single quote into the program, without having to engage in ugly shell quoting tricks.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In these cases, it is more convenient to put the program into a separate file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The -f instructs the `awk` utility to get the `awk` program from the file *source-file* (see Command-Line Options).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Any file name can be used for *source-file*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This was explained earlier (see Running `awk` Without Input Files).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Note that you don’t usually need single quotes around the file name that you specify with -f, because most file names don’t contain any of the shell’s special characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] (If your file names have spaces in them, then you will need the single quotes.) Notice that in advice, the `awk` program did not have single quotes around it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The quotes are only needed for programs that are provided on the `awk` command line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If you want to clearly identify an `awk` program file as such, you can add the extension .awk to the file name.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This doesn’t affect the execution of the `awk` program but it does make “housekeeping” easier.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Once you have learned `awk`, you may want to write self-contained `awk` scripts, using the ‘#!’ script mechanism.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Self-contained `awk` scripts are useful when you want to write a program that users can invoke without their having to know that the program is written in `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] For short to medium-length `awk` programs, it is most convenient to enter the program on the `awk` command line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This is best done by enclosing the entire program in single quotes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Once you are working with the shell, it is helpful to have a basic knowledge of shell quoting rules.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The following rules apply only to POSIX-compliant, Bourne-style shells (such as Bash, the GNU Bourne-Again Shell).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If you use the C shell, you’re on your own.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Before diving into the rules, we introduce a concept that appears throughout this Web page, which is that of the *null*, or empty, string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The null string is character data that has no value.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] It is written in `awk` programs like this: `""`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In the shell, it can be written using single or double quotes: `''` or `""`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Although the null string has no characters in it, it does exist.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Here, the `echo` utility receives a single argument, even though that argument has no characters in it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In the rest of this Web page, we use the terms *null string* and *empty string* interchangeably.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Mixing single and double quotes is difficult.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This program consists of three concatenated quoted strings.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The first and the third are single-quoted, and the second is double-quoted.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Judge for yourself which of these two is the more readable.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This option is also painful, because double quotes, backslashes, and dollar signs are very common in more advanced `awk` programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This works nicely, but you should comment clearly what the escape sequences mean.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If you really need both single and double quotes in your `awk` program, it is probably best to move it into a separate file, where the shell won’t be part of the picture and you can say what you mean.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Although this Web page generally only worries about POSIX systems and the POSIX shell, the following issue arises often enough for many users that it is worth addressing.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The “shells” on Microsoft Windows systems use the double-quote character for quoting, and make it difficult or impossible to include an escaped double quote character in a command-line script.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In this example the ‘\042’ is the octal code for a double quote; `gawk` converts it into a real double-quote for output by the `print` statement.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In MS-Windows escaping double quotes is a little tricky because you use backslashes to escape double quotes, but backslashes themselves are not escaped in the usual way; indeed they are either duplicated or not, depending upon whether there is a subsequent double quote.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Let *N* be the number of backslash(es) tailing the original string, *N* might be zero.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Surround the resulting string by double quotes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] However, the use of ‘\042’ instead of ‘\\\"’ is also possible and easier to read, because backslashes that are not followed by a double quote don’t need duplication.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Many of the examples in this Web page take their input from two sample data files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The first, mail-list, represents a list of peoples’ names together with their email addresses and information about those people.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The second data file, called inventory-shipped, contains information about monthly shipments.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In both files, each line is considered to be one *record*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In mail-list, each record contains the name of a person, his/her phone number, his/her email address, and a code for his/her relationship with the author of the list.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] An ‘A’ in the last column means that the person is an acquaintance.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] An ‘F’ in the last column means that the person is a friend.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The data file inventory-shipped represents information about shipments during the year.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Each record contains the month, the number of green crates shipped, the number of red boxes shipped, the number of orange bags shipped, and the number of blue packages shipped, respectively.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] There are 16 entries, covering the 12 months of last year and the first four months of the current year.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The sample files are included in the `gawk` distribution, in the directory awklib/eg/data.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] When lines containing ‘li’ are found, they are printed because ‘print $0’ means print the current line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] You will notice that slashes (‘/’) surround the string ‘li’ in the `awk` program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The slashes indicate that ‘li’ is the pattern to search for.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This type of pattern is called a *regular expression*, which is covered in more detail later (see Regular Expressions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The pattern is allowed to match parts of words.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] There are single quotes around the `awk` program so that the shell won’t interpret any of it as special shell characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In an `awk` rule, either the pattern or the action can be omitted, but not both.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If the pattern is omitted, then the action is performed for *every* input line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If the action is omitted, the default action is to print all lines that match the pattern.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Thus, we could leave out the action (the `print` statement and the braces) in the previous example and the result would be the same: `awk` prints all lines matching the pattern ‘li’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] By comparison, omitting the `print` statement but retaining the braces makes an empty action that does nothing (i.e., no lines are printed).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Many practical `awk` programs are just a line or two long.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Following is a collection of useful, short programs to get you started.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Some of these programs contain constructs that haven’t been covered yet.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] (The description of the program will give you a good idea of what is going on, but you’ll need to read the rest of the Web page to become an `awk` expert!) Most of the examples use a data file named data.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This is just a placeholder; if you use these programs yourself, substitute your own file names for data.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Some of the following examples use the output of ‘ls -l’ as input.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] `ls` is a system command that gives you a listing of the files in a directory.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] With the -l option, this listing includes each file’s size and the date the file was last modified.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The first field contains read-write permissions, the second field contains the number of links to the file, and the third field identifies the file’s owner.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The fourth field identifies the file’s group.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The fifth field contains the file’s size in bytes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The sixth, seventh, and eighth fields contain the month, day, and time, respectively, that the file was last modified.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Finally, the ninth field contains the file name.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] For future reference, note that there is often more than one way to do things in `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The `awk` utility reads the input files one line at a time.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] For each line, `awk` tries the patterns of each rule.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If several patterns match, then several actions execute in the order in which they appear in the `awk` program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If no patterns match, then no actions run.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] After processing all the rules that match the line (and perhaps there are none), `awk` reads the next line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] (However, see The `next` Statement and also see The `nextfile` Statement.) This continues until the program reaches the end of the file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The first rule has the string ‘12’ as the pattern and ‘print $0’ as the action.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The second rule has the string ‘21’ as the pattern and also has ‘print $0’ as the action.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Each rule’s action is enclosed in its own pair of braces.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This program prints every line that contains the string ‘12’ *or* the string ‘21’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If a line contains both strings, it is printed twice, once by each rule.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Note how the line beginning with ‘Jean-Paul’ in mail-list was printed twice, once for each rule.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Now that we’ve mastered some simple tasks, let’s look at what typical `awk` programs do.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This example shows how `awk` can be used to summarize, select, and rearrange the output of another utility.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This command prints the total number of bytes in all the files in the current directory that were last modified in November (of any year).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] As a reminder, the output of ‘ls -l’ gives you a listing of the files in a directory, including each file’s size and the date the file was last modified.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The ‘$6 == "Nov"’ in our `awk` program is an expression that tests whether the sixth field of the output from ‘ls -l’ matches the string ‘Nov’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Each time a line has the string ‘Nov’ for its sixth field, `awk` performs the action ‘sum += $5’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This adds the fifth field (the file’s size) to the variable `sum`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] As a result, when `awk` has finished reading all the input lines, `sum` is the total of the sizes of the files whose lines matched the pattern.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] After the last line of output from `ls` has been processed, the `END` rule executes and prints the value of `sum`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In this example, the value of `sum` is 80600.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] These more advanced `awk` techniques are covered in later sections (see Actions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Before you can move on to more advanced `awk` programming, you have to know how `awk` interprets your input and displays your output.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] By manipulating fields and using `print` statements, you can produce some very useful and impressive-looking reports.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If you would like to split a single statement into two lines at a point where a newline would terminate it, you can *continue* it by ending the first line with a backslash character (‘\’).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The backslash must be the final character on the line in order to be recognized as a continuation character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] A backslash followed by a newline is allowed anywhere in the statement, even in the middle of a string or regular expression.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] We have generally not used backslash continuation in our sample programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] `gawk` places no limit on the length of a line, so backslash continuation is never strictly necessary; it just makes programs more readable.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] For this same reason, as well as for clarity, we have kept most statements short in the programs presented throughout the Web page.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Backslash continuation is most useful when your `awk` program is in a separate source file instead of entered from the command line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] You should also note that many `awk` implementations are more particular about where you may use backslash continuation.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] For example, they may not allow you to split a string constant using backslash continuation.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Thus, for maximum portability of your `awk` programs, it is best not to split your lines in the middle of a regular expression or a string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Each rule’s action has to begin on the same line as the pattern.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] To have the pattern and action on separate lines, you *must* use backslash continuation; there is no other option.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Another thing to keep in mind is that backslash continuation and comments do not mix.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] As soon as `awk` sees the ‘#’ that starts a comment, it ignores *everything* on the rest of the line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In this case, it looks like the backslash would continue the comment onto the next line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] However, the backslash-newline combination is never even noticed because it is “hidden” inside the comment.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Thus, the `BEGIN` is noted as a syntax error.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Backslash continuation comes into play in an additional, unexpected situation.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This command line assigns a value to `FS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] There are several possibilities, and in fact different versions of `awk` do different things.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In short, the backslash and newline are removed, assigning `"a"` to `FS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This same treatment applies to variable assignments made with the -v option (see Command-Line Options) and to regular command-line variable assignments (see Assigning Variables on the Command Line).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If you’re interested, see https://lists.gnu.org/archive/html/bug-gawk/2022-10/msg00025.html for a source code patch that allows lines to be continued when inside parentheses.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This patch was not added to `gawk` since it would quietly decrease the portability of `awk` programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] When `awk` statements within one rule are short, you might want to put more than one of them on a line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This is accomplished by separating the statements with a semicolon (‘;’).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This also applies to the rules themselves.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The `awk` language provides a number of predefined, or *built-in*, variables that your programs can use to get information from `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] There are other variables your program can set as well to control how `awk` processes your data.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] In addition, `awk` provides a number of built-in functions for doing common computational and string-related operations.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] `gawk` provides built-in functions for working with timestamps, performing bit manipulation, for runtime string translation (internationalization), determining the type of a variable, and array sorting.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] As we develop our presentation of the `awk` language, we will introduce most of the variables and many of the functions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] They are described systematically in Predefined Variables and in Built-in Functions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Now that you’ve seen some of what `awk` can do, you might wonder how `awk` could be useful for you.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] By using utility programs, advanced patterns, field separators, arithmetic statements, and other selection criteria, you can produce much more complex output.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The `awk` language is very useful for producing reports from large amounts of raw data, such as summarizing information from the output of other utility programs like `ls`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Programs written with `awk` are usually much smaller than they would be in other languages.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] This makes `awk` programs easy to compose and use.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Often, `awk` programs can be quickly composed at your keyboard, used once, and thrown away.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Because `awk` programs are interpreted, you can avoid the (usually lengthy) compilation part of the typical edit-compile-test-debug cycle of software development.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] Complex programs have been written in `awk`, including a complete retargetable assembler for eight-bit microprocessors (see Glossary, for more information), and a microcode assembler for a special-purpose Prolog computer.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The original `awk`’s capabilities were strained by tasks of such complexity, but modern versions are more capable.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] If you find yourself writing `awk` scripts of more than, say, a few hundred lines, you might consider using a different programming language.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p02] The shell is good at string and pattern matching; in addition, it allows powerful use of the system utilities.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This chapter covers how to run `awk`, both POSIX-standard and `gawk`-specific command-line options, and what `awk` and `gawk` do with nonoption arguments.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] It then proceeds to cover how `gawk` searches for source files, reading standard input along with other files, `gawk`’s environment variables, `gawk`’s exit status, using include files, and obsolete and undocumented options and/or features.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Many of the options and features described here are discussed in more detail later in the Web page; feel free to skip over things in this chapter that don’t interest you right now.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] There are two ways to run `awk`—with an explicit program or with one or more program files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In addition to traditional one-letter POSIX-style options, `gawk` also supports GNU long options.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Doing so makes little sense, though; `awk` exits silently when given an empty program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] (d.c.) If --lint has been specified on the command line, `gawk` issues a warning that the program is empty.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Options begin with a dash and consist of a single character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] GNU-style long options consist of two dashes and a keyword.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The keyword can be abbreviated, as long as the abbreviation allows the option to be uniquely identified.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If the option takes an argument, either the keyword is immediately followed by an equals sign (‘=’) and the argument’s value, or the keyword and the argument’s value are separated by whitespace (spaces or TABs).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If a particular option with a value is given more than once, it is (usually) the last value that counts.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Each long option for `gawk` has a corresponding POSIX-style short option.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The long and short options are interchangeable in all contexts.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Set the `FS` variable to *fs* (see Specifying How Fields Are Separated).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Read the `awk` program source from *source-file* instead of in the first nonoption argument.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This option may be given multiple times; the `awk` program consists of the concatenation of the contents of each specified *source-file*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Files named with -f are treated as if they had ‘@namespace "awk"’ at their beginning.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] See Changing The Namespace, for more information on this advanced feature.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Set the variable *var* to the value *val* *before* execution of the program begins.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Such variable values are available inside the `BEGIN` rule (see Other Command-Line Arguments).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The -v option can only set one variable, but it can be used more than once, setting another variable each time, like this: ‘awk -v foo=1 -v bar=2 …’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Provide an implementation-specific option.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This is the POSIX convention for providing implementation-specific options.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] These options also have corresponding GNU-style long options.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Note that the long options may be abbreviated, as long as the abbreviations remain unique.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The full list of `gawk`-specific options is provided next.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Signal the end of the command-line options.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The following arguments are not treated as options even if they begin with ‘-’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This interpretation of -- follows the POSIX argument parsing conventions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This is useful if you have file names that start with ‘-’, or in shell scripts, if you have file names that will be specified by the user that could start with ‘-’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] It is also useful for passing options on to the `awk` program; see Processing Command-Line Options.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Cause `gawk` to treat all input data as single-byte characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In addition, all output written with `print` or `printf` is treated as single-byte characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Normally, `gawk` follows the POSIX standard and attempts to process its input data according to the current locale (see Where You Are Makes a Difference).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This can often involve converting multibyte characters into wide characters (internally), and can lead to problems or confusion if the input data does not contain valid multibyte characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Specify *compatibility mode*, in which the GNU extensions to the `awk` language are disabled, so that `gawk` behaves just like BWK `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] See Extensions in `gawk` Not in POSIX `awk`, which summarizes the extensions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Also see Downward Compatibility and Debugging.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Print the short version of the General Public License and then exit.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Print a sorted list of global variables, their types, and final values to *file*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If no *file* is provided, print this list to a file named awkvars.out in the current directory.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] No space is allowed between the -d and *file*, if *file* is supplied.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Having a list of all global variables is a good way to look for typographical errors in your programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] You would also use this option if you have a large program with a lot of functions, and you want to be sure that your functions don’t inadvertently use global variables that you meant to be local.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Enable debugging of `awk` programs (see Introduction to the `gawk` Debugger).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] By default, the debugger reads commands interactively from the keyboard (standard input).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The optional *file* argument allows you to specify a file with a list of commands for the debugger to execute noninteractively.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Provide program source code in the *program-text*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This option allows you to mix source code in files with source code that you enter on the command line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This is particularly useful when you have library functions that you want to use from your command-line programs (see The `AWKPATH` Environment Variable).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Note that `gawk` treats each string as if it ended with a newline character (even if it doesn’t).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This makes building the total program easier.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Similar to -f, read `awk` program text from *file*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Analyze the source program and generate a GNU `gettext` portable object template file on standard output for all string constants that have been marked for translation.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] See Internationalization with `gawk`, for information about this option.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Print a “usage” message summarizing the short- and long-style options that `gawk` accepts and then exit.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Read an `awk` source library from *source-file*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This option is completely equivalent to using the `@include` directive inside your program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] It is very similar to the -f option, but there are two important differences.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] First, when -i is used, the program source is not loaded if it has been previously loaded, whereas with -f, `gawk` always loads the file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Second, because this option is intended to be used with code libraries, `gawk` does not recognize such files as constituting main program input.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Thus, after processing an -i argument, `gawk` still expects to find the main source code via the -f option or on the command line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Files named with -i are treated as if they had ‘@namespace "awk"’ at their beginning.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] See Changing The Namespace, for more information.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Print the internal byte code names as they are executed when running the program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Each “op code” is preceded by a `+` sign in the output.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Enable special processing for files with comma separated values (CSV).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] See Working With Comma Separated Value Files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This option cannot be used with --posix.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Extensions are stored as system shared libraries.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This option searches for the library using the `AWKLIBPATH` environment variable.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The correct library suffix for your platform will be supplied by default, so it need not be specified in the extension name.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The extension initialization routine should be named `dl_load()`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] An alternative is to use the `@load` directive inside the program to load a shared library.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This advanced feature is described in detail in Writing Extensions for `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Warn about constructs that are dubious or nonportable to other `awk` implementations.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] No space is allowed between the -L and *value*, if *value* is supplied.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Some warnings are issued when `gawk` first reads your program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Others are issued at runtime, as your program executes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Cause lint warnings become fatal errors.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This may be drastic, but its use will certainly encourage the development of cleaner `awk` programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Only issue warnings about things that are actually invalid are issued.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Disable warnings about `gawk` extensions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Some warnings are only printed once, even if the dubious constructs they warn about occur multiple times in your `awk` program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Thus, when eliminating problems pointed out by --lint, you should take care to search for all occurrences of each inappropriate construct.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] As `awk` programs are usually short, doing so is not burdensome.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Select arbitrary-precision arithmetic on numbers.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This option has no effect if `gawk` is not compiled to use the GNU MPFR and MP libraries (see Arithmetic and Arbitrary-Precision Arithmetic with `gawk`).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] As of version 5.2, the arbitrary precision arithmetic features in `gawk` are “on parole.” The primary maintainer is no longer willing to support this feature, but another member of the development team has stepped up to take it over.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] As long as this situation remains stable, MPFR will be supported.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If it changes, the MPFR support will be removed from `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Enable automatic interpretation of octal and hexadecimal values in input data (see Allowing Nondecimal Input Data).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Force the use of the locale’s decimal point character when parsing numeric input data (see Where You Are Makes a Difference).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Enable pretty-printing of `awk` programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] By default, the output program is created in a file named awkprof.out (see Profiling Your `awk` Programs).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The optional *file* argument allows you to specify a different file name for the output.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] No space is allowed between the -o and *file*, if *file* is supplied.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Enable `gawk`’s default optimizations on the internal representation of the program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] At the moment, this includes just simple constant folding.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This option remains primarily for backwards compatibility.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] However, it may be used to cancel the effect of an earlier -s option (see later in this list).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Enable profiling of `awk` programs (see Profiling Your `awk` Programs).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] By default, profiles are created in a file named awkprof.out.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The optional *file* argument allows you to specify a different file name for the profile file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] No space is allowed between the -p and *file*, if *file* is supplied.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The profile contains execution counts for each statement in the program in the left margin, and function call counts for each function.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This disables all `gawk` extensions (just like --traditional) and disables all extensions not allowed by POSIX.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] See Common Extensions Summary for a summary of the extensions in `gawk` that are disabled by this option.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If you supply both --traditional and --posix on the command line, --posix takes precedence.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] `gawk` issues a warning if both options are supplied.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Allow interval expressions (see Regular Expression Operators) in regexps.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Nevertheless, this option remains for backward compatibility.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Disable `gawk`’s default optimizations on the internal representation of the program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Disable the `system()` function, input redirections with `getline`, output redirections with `print` and `printf`, and dynamic extensions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Also, disallow adding file names to `ARGV` that were not there when `gawk` started running.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This is particularly useful when you want to run `awk` scripts from questionable sources and need to make sure the scripts can’t access your system (other than the specified input data files).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Warn about constructs that are not available in the original version of `awk` from Version 7 Unix (see Major Changes Between V7 and SVR3.1).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Print version information for this particular copy of `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This allows you to determine if your copy of `gawk` is up to date with respect to whatever the Free Software Foundation is currently distributing.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] It is also useful for bug reports (see Reporting Problems and Bugs).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Any command-line arguments following `--` are placed in `ARGV`, even if they start with a minus sign.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In compatibility mode, as long as program text has been supplied, any other options are flagged as invalid with a warning message but are otherwise ignored.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In compatibility mode, as a special case, if the value of *fs* supplied to the -F option is ‘t’, then `FS` is set to the TAB character (`"\t"`).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This is true only for --traditional and not for --posix (see Specifying How Fields Are Separated).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The -f option may be used more than once on the command line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If it is, `awk` reads its program source from all of the named files, as if they had been concatenated together into one big file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This is useful for creating libraries of `awk` functions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] These functions can be written once and then retrieved from a standard place, instead of having to be included in each individual program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The -i option is similar in this regard.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] With standard `awk`, library functions can still be used, even if the program is entered at the keyboard, by specifying ‘-f /dev/tty’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] After typing your program, type Ctrl-d (the end-of-file character) to terminate it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Because it is clumsy using the standard `awk` mechanisms to mix source file and command-line `awk` programs, `gawk` provides the -e option.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This does not require you to preempt the standard input for your source code, and it allows you to easily mix command-line and library source code (see The `AWKPATH` Environment Variable).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] As with -f, the -e and -i options may also be used multiple times on the command line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If no -f option (or -e option for `gawk`) is specified, then `awk` uses the first nonoption command-line argument as the text of the program source code.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Arguments on the command line that follow the program text are entered into the `ARGV` array; `awk` does *not* continue to parse the command line looking for options.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If the environment variable `POSIXLY_CORRECT` exists, then `gawk` behaves in strict POSIX mode, exactly as if you had supplied --posix.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Many GNU programs look for this environment variable to suppress extensions that conflict with POSIX, but `gawk` behaves differently: it suppresses all extensions, even those that do not conflict with POSIX, and behaves in strict POSIX mode.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If --lint is supplied on the command line and `gawk` turns on POSIX mode because of `POSIXLY_CORRECT`, then it issues a warning message indicating that POSIX mode is in effect.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] You would typically set this variable in your shell’s startup file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Having `POSIXLY_CORRECT` set is not recommended for daily use, but it is good for testing the portability of your programs to other environments.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Any additional arguments on the command line are normally treated as input files to be processed in the order specified.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] However, an argument that has the form `*var*=*value*`, assigns the value *value* to the variable *var*—it does not specify a file at all.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] All the command-line arguments are made available to your `awk` program in the `ARGV` array (see Predefined Variables).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Command-line options and the program text (if present) are omitted from `ARGV`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] All other arguments, including variable assignments, are included.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] As each element of `ARGV` is processed, `gawk` sets `ARGIND` to the index in `ARGV` of the current element.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Changing `ARGC` and `ARGV` in your `awk` program lets you control how `awk` processes the input files; this is described in more detail in Using `ARGC` and `ARGV`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The distinction between file name arguments and variable-assignment arguments is made when `awk` is about to open the next input file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] At that point in execution, it checks the file name to see whether it is really a variable assignment; if so, `awk` sets the variable instead of reading a file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Therefore, the variables actually receive the given values after all previously specified files have been read.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In particular, the values of variables assigned in this fashion are *not* available inside a `BEGIN` rule (see The `BEGIN` and `END` Special Patterns), because such rules are run before `awk` begins scanning the argument list.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The variable values given on the command line are processed for escape sequences (see Escape Sequences).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In some very early implementations of `awk`, when a variable assignment occurred before any file names, the assignment would happen *before* the `BEGIN` rule was executed.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] `awk`’s behavior was thus inconsistent; some command-line assignments were available inside the `BEGIN` rule, while others were not.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Unfortunately, some applications came to depend upon this “feature.” When `awk` was changed to be more consistent, the -v option was added to accommodate applications that depended upon the old behavior.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The variable assignment feature is most useful for assigning to variables such as `RS`, `OFS`, and `ORS`, which control input and output formats, before scanning the data files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] It is also useful for controlling state if multiple passes are needed over a data file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Given the variable assignment feature, the -F option for setting the value of `FS` is not strictly necessary.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] It remains for historical compatibility.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Often, you may wish to read standard input together with other files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] For example, you may wish to read one file, read standard input coming from a pipe, and then read another file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The way to name the standard input, with all versions of `awk`, is to use a single, standalone minus sign or dash, ‘-’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Here, `awk` first reads file1, then it reads the output of *some_command*, and finally it reads file2.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] You may also use `"-"` to name standard input when reading files with `getline` (see Using `getline` from a File).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] And, you can even use `"-"` with the -f option to read program source code from standard input (see Command-Line Options).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In addition, `gawk` allows you to specify the special file name /dev/stdin, both on the command line and with `getline`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Some other versions of `awk` also support this, but it is not standard.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] A number of environment variables influence how `gawk` behaves.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In most `awk` implementations, you must supply a precise pathname for each program file, unless the file is in the current directory.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] But with `gawk`, if the file name supplied to the -f or -i options does not contain a directory separator ‘/’, then `gawk` searches a list of directories (called the *search path*) one by one, looking for a file with the specified name.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The search path is a string consisting of directory names separated by colons.13 `gawk` gets its search path from the `AWKPATH` environment variable.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If that variable does not exist, or if it has an empty value, `gawk` uses a default path (described shortly).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The search path feature is particularly helpful for building libraries of useful `awk` functions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The library files can be placed in a standard directory in the default path and then specified on the command line with a short file name.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Otherwise, you would have to type the full file name for each file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] By using the -i or -f options, your command-line `awk` programs can use facilities in `awk` library files (see A Library of `awk` Functions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Path searching is always done, even if `gawk` is in compatibility mode.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This is true for both --traditional and --posix.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If the source code file is not found after the initial search, the path is searched again after adding the suffix ‘.awk’ to the file name.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] `gawk`’s path search mechanism is similar to the shell’s.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] (See *The Bourne-Again SHell manual*.) It treats a null entry in the path as indicating the current directory.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The default value for `AWKPATH` is ‘.:/usr/local/share/awk’.14 Since . is included at the beginning, `gawk` searches first in the current directory and then in /usr/local/share/awk.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In practice, this means that you will rarely need to change the value of `AWKPATH`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] See Shell Startup Files, for information on functions that help to manipulate the `AWKPATH` variable.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] `gawk` places the value of the search path that it used into `ENVIRON["AWKPATH"]`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This provides access to the actual search path value from within an `awk` program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Although you can change `ENVIRON["AWKPATH"]` within your `awk` program, this has no effect on the running program’s behavior.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This makes sense: the `AWKPATH` environment variable is used to find the program source files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Once your program is running, all the files have been found, and `gawk` no longer needs to use `AWKPATH`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The `AWKLIBPATH` environment variable is similar to the `AWKPATH` variable, but it is used to search for loadable extensions (stored as system shared libraries) specified with the -l option rather than for source files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If the extension is not found, the path is searched again after adding the appropriate shared library suffix for the platform.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] For example, on GNU/Linux systems, the suffix ‘.so’ is used.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The search path specified is also used for extensions loaded via the `@load` directive (see Loading Dynamic Extensions into Your Program).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] See Shell Startup Files, for information on functions that help to manipulate the `AWKLIBPATH` variable.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] `gawk` places the value of the search path that it used into `ENVIRON["AWKLIBPATH"]`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Although you can change `ENVIRON["AWKLIBPATH"]` within your `awk` program, this has no effect on the running program’s behavior.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This makes sense: the `AWKLIBPATH` environment variable is used to find any requested extensions, and they are loaded before the program starts to run.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Once your program is running, all the extensions have been found, and `gawk` no longer needs to use `AWKLIBPATH`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] A number of other environment variables affect `gawk`’s behavior, but they are more specialized.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Specifies the interval between connection retries, in milliseconds.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] On systems that do not support the `usleep()` system call, the value is rounded up to an integral number of seconds.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Specifies the backing file to use for persistent storage of `gawk`’s variables and arrays.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Specifies the time, in milliseconds, for `gawk` to wait for input before returning with an error.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Controls the number of times `gawk` attempts to retry a two-way TCP/IP (socket) connection before giving up.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] See Using `gawk` for Network Programming.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Note that when nonfatal I/O is enabled (see Enabling Nonfatal Output), `gawk` only tries to open a TCP/IP socket once.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Controls the verbosity of the persistent memory allocator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Causes `gawk` to switch to POSIX-compatibility mode, disabling all traditional and GNU extensions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The environment variables in the following list are meant for use by the `gawk` developers for testing and tuning.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This variable only affects `gawk` on POSIX-compliant systems.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] With a value of ‘exact’, `gawk` uses the size of each input file as the size of the memory buffer to allocate for I/O.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Otherwise, the value should be a number, and `gawk` uses that number as the size of the buffer to allocate.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If this variable exists with a value of ‘gst’, `gawk` switches to using the hash function from GNU Smalltalk for managing arrays.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] With a value of ‘fnv1a’, `gawk` uses the FNV1-A hash function.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] These functions may be marginally faster than the standard function.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If this variable exists, `gawk` switches to reading source files one line at a time, instead of reading in blocks.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This exists for debugging problems on filesystems on non-POSIX operating systems where I/O is performed in records, not in blocks.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If this variable exists, `gawk` includes the file name and line number within the `gawk` source code from which warning and/or fatal messages are generated.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Its purpose is to help isolate the source of a message, as there are multiple places that produce the same warning or error message.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Specifies the location of compiled message object files for `gawk` itself.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This is passed to the `bindtextdomain()` function when `gawk` starts up.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If this variable exists, `gawk` does not use the DFA regexp matcher for “does it match” kinds of tests.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Its purpose is to help isolate differences between the two regexp matchers that `gawk` uses internally.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This specifies the amount by which `gawk` should grow its internal evaluation stack, when needed.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This specifies intended maximum number of items `gawk` will maintain on a hash chain for managing arrays indexed by integers.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This specifies intended maximum number of items `gawk` will maintain on a hash chain for managing arrays indexed by strings.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If this variable exists, `gawk` uses the `mtrace()` library calls from the GNU C library to help track down possible memory leaks.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This cannot be used together with the persistent memory allocator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If the `exit` statement is used with a value (see The `exit` Statement), then `gawk` exits with the numeric value given to it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Otherwise, if there were no problems during execution, `gawk` exits with the value of the C constant `EXIT_SUCCESS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If an error occurs, `gawk` exits with the value of the C constant `EXIT_FAILURE`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If `gawk` exits because of a fatal error, the exit status is two.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] On non-POSIX systems, this value may be mapped to `EXIT_FAILURE`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This section describes a feature that is specific to `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] It discusses how one source file may include another.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The `@include` directive can be used to read external `awk` source files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This gives you the ability to split large `awk` source files into smaller, more manageable pieces, and also lets you reuse common `awk` code from various `awk` scripts.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In other words, you can group together `awk` functions used to carry out specific tasks into external files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] These files can be used just like function libraries, using the `@include` directive in conjunction with the `AWKPATH` environment variable.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Note that source files may also be included using the -i option.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] We’ll start with two (trivial) `awk` scripts, namely test1 and test2.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] `gawk` runs the test2 script, which includes test1 using the `@include` directive.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] So, to include external `awk` source files, you just use `@include` followed by the name of the file to be included, enclosed in double quotes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The file name can, of course, be a pathname.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The `AWKPATH` environment variable can be of great value when using `@include`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The same rules for the use of the `AWKPATH` variable in command-line file searches (see The `AWKPATH` Environment Variable) apply to `@include` also.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This is very helpful in constructing `gawk` function libraries.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If you have a large script with useful, general-purpose `awk` functions, you can break it down into library files and put those files in a special directory.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] You can then include those “libraries,” either by using the full pathnames of the files, or by setting the `AWKPATH` environment variable accordingly and then using `@include` with just the file part of the full pathname.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Of course, you can keep library files in more than one directory; the more complex the working environment is, the more directories you may need to organize the files to be included.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Given the ability to specify multiple -f options, the `@include` mechanism is not strictly necessary.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] However, the `@include` directive can help you in constructing self-contained `gawk` programs, thus reducing the need for writing complex and tedious command lines.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] In particular, `@include` is very useful for writing CGI scripts to be run from web pages.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The `@include` directive and the -i/--include command line option are completely equivalent.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] An included program source is not loaded if it has been previously loaded.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The rules for finding a source file described in The `AWKPATH` Environment Variable also apply to files loaded with `@include`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Finally, files included with `@include` are treated as if they had ‘@namespace "awk"’ at their beginning.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] However, there is a separate `@nsinclude` command which does not change the namespace; see Including A File Without Changing The Namespace.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The `@load` directive can be used to read external `awk` extensions (stored as system shared libraries).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This allows you to link in compiled code that may offer superior performance and/or give you access to extended capabilities not supported by the `awk` language.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] The `AWKLIBPATH` variable is used to search for the extension.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Using `@load` is completely equivalent to using the -l command-line option.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If the extension is not initially found in `AWKLIBPATH`, another search is conducted after appending the platform’s default shared library suffix to the file name.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] For command-line usage, the -l option is more convenient, but `@load` is useful for embedding inside an `awk` source file that requires access to an extension.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] Writing Extensions for `gawk`, describes how to write extensions (in C or C++) that can be loaded with either `@load` or the -l option.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] It also describes the `ordchr` extension.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] This section describes features and/or command-line options from previous releases of `gawk` that either are not available in the current version or are still supported but deprecated (meaning that they will *not* be in a future release).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] As of `gawk` version 5.2, the arbitrary precision arithmetic feature is “on parole.” This feature is now being supported by a volunteer in the development team and not by the primary maintainer.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] If this situation changes, then the feature will be removed.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p03] For more information see Arbitrary Precision Arithmetic is On Parole!.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] A *regular expression*, or *regexp*, is a way of describing a set of strings.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Because regular expressions are such a fundamental part of `awk` programming, their format and use deserve a separate chapter.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] A regular expression enclosed in slashes (‘/’) is an `awk` pattern that matches every input record whose text belongs to that set.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The simplest regular expression is a sequence of letters, numbers, or both.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Such a regexp matches any string that contains that sequence.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Thus, the regexp ‘foo’ matches any string containing ‘foo’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Thus, the pattern `/foo/` matches any input record containing the three adjacent characters ‘foo’ *anywhere* in the record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Other kinds of regexps let you specify more complicated classes of strings.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Initially, the examples in this chapter are simple.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] As we explain more about how regular expressions work, we present more complicated instances.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] A regular expression can be used as a pattern by enclosing it in slashes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Then the regular expression is tested against the entire text of each record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Regular expressions can also be used in matching expressions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] These expressions allow you to specify the string to match against; it need not be the entire current input record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The two operators ‘~’ and ‘!~’ perform regular expression comparisons.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Expressions using these operators can be used as patterns, or in `if`, `while`, `for`, and `do` statements.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] When a regexp is enclosed in slashes, such as `/foo/`, we call it a *regexp constant*, much like `5.27` is a numeric constant and `"foo"` is a string constant.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Some characters cannot be included literally in string constants (`"foo"`) or regexp constants (`/foo/`).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Instead, they should be represented with *escape sequences*, which are character sequences beginning with a backslash (‘\’).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] One use of an escape sequence is to include a double quote character in a string constant.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Because a plain double quote ends the string, you must use ‘\"’ to represent an actual double quote character as a part of the string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The backslash character itself is another character that cannot be included normally; you must write ‘\\’ to put one backslash in the string or regexp.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Thus, the string whose contents are the two characters ‘"’ and ‘\’ must be written `"\"\\"`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Other escape sequences represent unprintable characters such as TAB or newline.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] There is nothing to stop you from entering most unprintable characters directly in a string constant or regexp constant, but they may look ugly.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The following list presents all the escape sequences used in `awk` and what they represent.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The “alert” character, Ctrl-g, ASCII code 7 (BEL).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Carriage return, Ctrl-m, ASCII code 13 (CR).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Horizontal TAB, Ctrl-i, ASCII code 9 (HT).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Vertical TAB, Ctrl-k, ASCII code 11 (VT).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The octal value *nnn*, where *nnn* stands for 1 to 3 digits between ‘0’ and ‘7’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, the code for the ASCII ESC (escape) character is ‘\033’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The hexadecimal value *hh*, where *hh* stands for a sequence of hexadecimal digits (‘0’–‘9’, and either ‘A’–‘F’ or ‘a’–‘f’).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] A maximum of two digits are allowed after the ‘\x’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Any further hexadecimal digits are treated as simple letters or numbers.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The hexadecimal value *hh*, where *hh* stands for a sequence of one or more hexadecimal digits (‘0’–‘9’, and either ‘A’–‘F’ or ‘a’–‘f’).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] A maximum of eight digits are allowed after the ‘\u’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This escape sequence is intended for designating a character in the current locale’s character set.16 `gawk` first converts the given digits into an integer and then translates the given “wide character” value into the current locale’s multibyte encoding.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] If the wide character value does not represent a valid character, or if the character is valid but cannot be encoded into the current locale’s multibyte encoding, the value becomes `"?"`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] `gawk` issues a warning message when this happens.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] A literal slash (should be used for regexp constants only).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This sequence is used when you want to write a regexp constant that contains a slash (such as `/.*:\/home\/[[:alnum:]]+:.*/`; the ‘[[:alnum:]]’ notation is discussed in Using Bracket Expressions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Because the regexp is delimited by slashes, you need to escape any slash that is part of the pattern, in order to tell `awk` to keep processing the rest of the regexp.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] A literal double quote (should be used for string constants only).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This sequence is used when you want to write a string constant that contains a double quote (such as `"He said \"hi!\" to her."`).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Because the string is delimited by double quotes, you need to escape any double quote that is part of the string, in order to tell `awk` to keep processing the rest of the string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In `gawk`, a number of additional two-character sequences that begin with a backslash have special meaning in regexps.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In a regexp, a backslash before any character that is not in the previous list and not listed in `gawk`-Specific Regexp Operators means that the next character should be taken literally, even if it would normally be a regexp operator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, `/a\+b/` matches the three characters ‘a+b’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For complete portability, do not use a backslash before any character not shown in the previous list or that is not a regular expression operator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] (The 2024 POSIX standard explicitly lists the operators that can be escaped, leaving it undefined as to what happens for any other escaped character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] You can combine regular expressions with special characters, called *regular expression operators* or *metacharacters*, to increase the power and versatility of regular expressions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The escape sequences described earlier in Escape Sequences are valid inside a regexp.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] They are introduced by a ‘\’ and are recognized and converted into corresponding real characters as the very first step in processing regexps.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This suppresses the special meaning of a character when matching.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, ‘\$’ matches the character ‘$’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This matches the beginning of a string. ‘^@chapter’ matches ‘@chapter’ at the beginning of a string, for example, and can be used to identify chapter beginnings in Texinfo source files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The ‘^’ is known as an *anchor*, because it anchors the pattern to match only at the beginning of the string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] It is important to realize that ‘^’ does not match the beginning of a line (the point right after a ‘\n’ newline character) embedded in a string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This is similar to ‘^’, but it matches only at the end of a string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, ‘p$’ matches a record that ends with a ‘p’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The ‘$’ is an anchor and does not match the end of a line (the point right before a ‘\n’ newline character) embedded in a string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This matches any single character, *including* the newline character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, ‘.P’ matches any single character followed by a ‘P’ in a string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Using concatenation, we can make a regular expression such as ‘U.A’, which matches any three-character sequence that begins with ‘U’ and ends with ‘A’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In strict POSIX mode (see Command-Line Options), ‘.’ does not match the NUL character, which is a character with all bits equal to zero.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Otherwise, NUL is just another character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Other versions of `awk` may not be able to match the NUL character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This is called a *bracket expression*.17 It matches any *one* of the characters that are enclosed in the square brackets.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, ‘[MVX]’ matches any one of the characters ‘M’, ‘V’, or ‘X’ in a string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] A full discussion of what can be inside the square brackets of a bracket expression is given in Using Bracket Expressions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This is a *complemented bracket expression*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The first character after the ‘[’ *must* be a ‘^’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] It matches any characters *except* those in the square brackets.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, ‘[^awk]’ matches any character that is not an ‘a’, ‘w’, or ‘k’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This is the *alternation operator* and it is used to specify alternatives.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The ‘|’ has the lowest precedence of all the regular expression operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, ‘^P|[aeiouy]’ matches any string that matches either ‘^P’ or ‘[aeiouy]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This means it matches any string that starts with ‘P’ or contains (anywhere within it) a lowercase English vowel.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The alternation applies to the largest possible regexps on either side.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Parentheses are used for grouping in regular expressions, as in arithmetic.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] They can be used to concatenate regular expressions containing the alternation operator, ‘|’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] (These are Texinfo formatting control sequences.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The left or opening parenthesis is always a metacharacter; to match one literally, precede it with a backslash.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] However, the right or closing parenthesis is only special when paired with a left parenthesis; an unpaired right parenthesis is (silently) treated as a regular character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This symbol means that the preceding regular expression should be repeated as many times as necessary to find a match.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, ‘ph*’ applies the ‘*’ symbol to the preceding ‘h’ and looks for matches of one ‘p’ followed by any number of ‘h’s.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This also matches just ‘p’ if no ‘h’s are present.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] There are two subtle points to understand about how ‘*’ works.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] First, the ‘*’ applies only to the single preceding regular expression component (e.g., in ‘ph*’, it applies just to the ‘h’).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] To cause ‘*’ to apply to a larger subexpression, use parentheses: ‘(ph)*’ matches ‘ph’, ‘phph’, ‘phphph’, and so on.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Second, ‘*’ finds as many repetitions as possible.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] If the text to be matched is ‘phhhhhhhhhhhhhhooey’, ‘ph*’ matches all of the ‘h’s.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Shortest match or *non-greedy* version of the ‘*’ operator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This operator and the other non-greedy operators are discussed separately, shortly, in Shortest Match, or “Non-greedy” Regexp Operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This symbol is similar to ‘*’, except that the preceding expression must be matched at least once.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This means that ‘wh+y’ would match ‘why’ and ‘whhy’, but not ‘wy’, whereas ‘wh*y’ would match all three.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Shortest match or non-greedy version of the ‘+’ operator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This symbol is similar to ‘*’, except that the preceding expression can be matched either once or not at all.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, ‘fe?d’ matches ‘fed’ and ‘fd’, but nothing else.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Shortest match or non-greedy version of the ‘?’ operator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] One or two numbers inside braces denote an *interval expression*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] If there is one number in the braces, the preceding regexp is repeated *n* times.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] If there are two numbers separated by a comma, the preceding regexp is repeated *n* to *m* times.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches ‘whhhy’, but not ‘why’ or ‘whhhhy’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches ‘whhhy’, ‘whhhhy’, or ‘whhhhhy’ only.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Shortest match or non-greedy versions of the ‘{}’ operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In regular expressions, the ‘*’, ‘+’, and ‘?’ operators, as well as the braces ‘{’ and ‘}’, have the highest precedence, followed by concatenation, and finally by ‘|’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] As in arithmetic, parentheses can change how operators are grouped.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] According to the POSIX specification, when ‘*’, ‘+’, ‘?’, or ‘{’ are not preceded by a character, the behavior is “undefined.” In practice, for `gawk`, the ‘*’, ‘+’, ‘?’ and ‘{’ operators stand for themselves when there is nothing in the regexp that precedes them.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, `/+/` matches a literal plus sign.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] However, many other versions of `awk` treat such a usage as a syntax error.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Interval expressions were not traditionally available in `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] They were added as part of the POSIX standard to make `awk` and `egrep` consistent with each other.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Initially, because old programs may use ‘{’ and ‘}’ in regexp constants, `gawk` did *not* match interval expressions in regexps.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] However, beginning with version 4.0, `gawk` does match interval expressions by default.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This is because compatibility with POSIX has become more important to most `gawk` users than compatibility with old programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For programs that use ‘{’ and ‘}’ in regexp constants, it is good practice to always escape them with a backslash.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] When ‘{’ and ‘}’ appear in regexp constants in a way that cannot be interpreted as an interval expression (such as `/q{a}/`), then they stand for themselves.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] As mentioned, interval expressions were not traditionally available in `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In March of 2019, BWK `awk` (finally) acquired them.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Starting with version 5.2, `gawk`’s --traditional option no longer disables interval expressions in regular expressions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] POSIX says that interval expressions containing repetition counts greater than 255 produce unspecified results.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Traditionally, regexps have always matched the leftmost, longest sequence of characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, given the text ‘abxxxcd’, the regexp ‘x+’ could match one, two, or all three ‘x’ characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] By defining a regexp to match the longest possible sequence, we know that ‘x+’ will match all three ‘x’s.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Such behavior may be termed *greedy*, since a regexp will match as many characters as possible.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The Perl language introduced “non-greedy,” or shortest-match operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In the above example, ‘x+’ would only match a single ‘x’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The 2024 POSIX standard introduced shortest-match operators into POSIX EREs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Syntactically, you create a shortest-match operator by appending a ‘?’ to one of the traditional regexp operators: ‘*’, ‘+’, ‘?’, or ‘{}’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The shortest-match operators don’t always match what you might think would be the smallest sequence of characters, since the general, leftmost-longest rule still applies to the overall regexp.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] To illustrate the differences, we use a program named shortest-match.awk.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This program takes several strings, and replaces the text matching a given pattern with a single ‘X’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The program uses a number of `gawk`-specific features which haven’t yet been described.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] We therefore delay presenting the code until Demonstrating Shortest and Longest Match Operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For the shortest match, only one ‘x’ is replaced.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For the longest match, every ‘x’ is replaced.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In this case, the result is the same, since the longest possible string of characters is matched.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The same total amount of text is matched for both patterns.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] However, the text matched by the subexpressions differs between the two cases.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In the longest-match case, the longest possible subexpressions match first.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] There is a ‘+’ on the outside, meaning that the total inner expression may match multiple times.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For the longest-match expression, that indeed happens.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The subexpressions two through four have the start and length values for the last occasion where the inner expression matched.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The shortest-match expression only matched the inner expression once.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Here, the results are identical; both the nature of the string to be matched and the POSIX longest-leftmost rule, cause this to happen.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The MinRX regular expression matching engine, which is `gawk`’s default matcher (see Selecting the Regexp Matching Engine), supports the shortest-match operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Also, when invoked with the --traditional option, shortest-match operators are not supported, since traditional `awk` does not have these operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] As mentioned earlier, a bracket expression matches any character among those listed between the opening and closing square brackets.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Within a bracket expression, a *range expression* consists of two characters separated by a hyphen.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] It matches any single character that sorts between the two characters, based upon the system’s native character set.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] (See Regexp Ranges and Locales: A Long Sad Story for an explanation of how the POSIX standard and `gawk` have changed over time.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] With the increasing popularity of the Unicode character standard, there is an additional wrinkle to consider.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Octal and hexadecimal escape sequences inside bracket expressions are taken to represent only single-byte characters (characters whose values fit within the range 0–255).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] To match a range of characters where the endpoints of the range are larger than 255, enter the multibyte encodings of the characters directly, or use the `\u` escape sequence.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] To include one of the characters ‘\’, ‘]’, ‘-’, or ‘^’ in a bracket expression, put a ‘\’ in front of it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Additionally, if you place ‘]’ right after the opening ‘[’ (‘[]d]’), the closing bracket is treated as one of the characters to be matched.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Inside bracket expressions, it’s not necessary to escape the other standard regular expression operators, such as ‘*’ and ‘?’, and for full portability you should not.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The treatment of ‘\’ in bracket expressions is compatible with other `awk` implementations and is also mandated by POSIX.19 The regular expressions in `awk` are a superset of the POSIX specification for Extended Regular Expressions (EREs).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] POSIX EREs are based on the regular expressions accepted by the traditional `egrep` utility.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] A character class is only valid in a regexp *inside* the brackets of a bracket expression.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Character classes consist of ‘[:’, a keyword denoting the class, and ‘:]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Table 3.1 lists the character classes defined by the POSIX standard.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, before the POSIX standard, you had to write `/[A-Za-z0-9]/` to match alphanumeric characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] If your character set had other alphabetic characters in it, this would not match them.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] With the POSIX character classes, you can write `/[[:alnum:]]/` to match the alphabetic and numeric characters in your character set.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Some utilities that match regular expressions provide a nonstandard ‘[:ascii:]’ character class; `awk` does not.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] However, you can simulate such a construct using ‘[\x00-\x7F]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This matches all values numerically between zero and 127, which is the defined range of the ASCII character set.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Use a complemented character list (‘[^\x00-\x7F]’) to match any single-byte characters that are not in the ASCII range.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Two additional special sequences can appear in bracket expressions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] These apply to non-ASCII character sets, which can have single symbols (called *collating elements*) that are represented with more than one character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] They can also have several characters that are equivalent for *collating*, or sorting, purposes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Multicharacter collating elements enclosed between ‘[.’ and ‘.]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, if ‘ch’ is a collating element, then ‘[[.ch.]]’ is a regexp that matches this collating element, whereas ‘[ch]’ is a regexp that matches either ‘c’ or ‘h’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Locale-specific names for a list of characters that are equal.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The name is enclosed between ‘[=’ and ‘=]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, the name ‘e’ might be used to represent all of “e,” “ê,” “è,” and “é.” In this case, ‘[[=e=]]’ is a regexp that matches any of ‘e’, ‘ê’, ‘é’, or ‘è’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] These features are very valuable in non-English-speaking locales.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Inside a bracket expression, an opening bracket (‘[’) that does not start a character class, collating element or equivalence class is taken literally.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This example uses the `sub()` function to make a change to the input record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] (`sub()` replaces the first instance of any text matched by the first argument with the string provided as the second argument; see String-Manipulation Functions.) Here, the regexp `/a+/` indicates “one or more ‘a’ characters,” and the replacement text is ‘<A>’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] `awk` (and POSIX) regular expressions always match the leftmost, *longest* sequence of input characters that can match.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For simple match/no-match tests, this is not so important.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] But when doing text matching and substitutions with the `match()`, `sub()`, `gsub()`, and `gensub()` functions, it is very important.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Understanding this principle is also important for regexp-based record and field splitting (see How Input Is Split into Records, and also see Specifying How Fields Are Separated).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The righthand side of a ‘~’ or ‘!~’ operator need not be a regexp constant (i.e., a string of characters between slashes).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The expression is evaluated and converted to a string if necessary; the contents of the string are then used as the regexp.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This sets `digits_regexp` to a regexp that describes one or more digits, and tests whether the input record matches this regexp.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] What difference does it make if the string is scanned twice?
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The answer has to do with escape sequences, and particularly with backslashes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] To get a backslash into a regular expression inside a string, you have to type two backslashes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, `/\*/` is a regexp constant for a literal ‘*’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] To do the same thing with a string, you have to type `"\\*"`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The first backslash escapes the second one so that the string actually contains the two characters ‘\’ and ‘*’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Given that you can use both regexp and string constants to describe regular expressions, which should you use?
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] GNU software that deals with regular expressions provides a number of additional regexp operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] These operators are described in this section and are specific to `gawk`; they are not available in other `awk` implementations.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Most of the additional operators deal with word matching.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches any space character as defined by the current locale.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Think of it as shorthand for ‘[[:space:]]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches any character that is not a space, as defined by the current locale.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Think of it as shorthand for ‘[^[:space:]]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches any word-constituent character—that is, it matches any letter, digit, or underscore.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Think of it as shorthand for ‘[[:alnum:]_]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches any character that is not word-constituent.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Think of it as shorthand for ‘[^[:alnum:]_]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches the empty string at the beginning of a word.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, `/\<away/` matches ‘away’ but not ‘stowaway’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches the empty string at the end of a word.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, `/stow\>/` matches ‘stow’ but not ‘stowaway’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches the empty string at either the beginning or the end of a word (i.e., the word boundar**y**).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, ‘\yballs?\y’ matches either ‘ball’ or ‘balls’, as a separate word.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Matches the empty string that occurs between two word-constituent characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] For example, `/\Brat\B/` matches ‘crate’, but it does not match ‘dirty rat’. ‘\B’ is essentially the opposite of ‘\y’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Another way to think of this is that ‘\B’ matches the empty string provided it’s not at the edge of a word.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] There are two other operators that work on buffers.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In Emacs, a *buffer* is, naturally, an Emacs buffer.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Other GNU programs, including `gawk`, consider the entire string to match as the buffer.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Because ‘^’ and ‘$’ always work in terms of the beginning and end of strings, these operators don’t add any new capabilities for `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] They are provided for compatibility with other GNU software.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In other GNU software, the word-boundary operator is ‘\b’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] However, that conflicts with the `awk` language’s definition of ‘\b’ as backspace, so `gawk` uses a different letter.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] An alternative method would have been to require two backslashes in the GNU operators, but this was deemed too confusing.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The current method of using ‘\y’ for the GNU ‘\b’ appears to be the lesser of two evils.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In the default case, `gawk` provides all the facilities of POSIX regexps and the previously described GNU regexp operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] GNU regexp operators described in Regular Expression Operators.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Match only POSIX regexps; the GNU operators are not special (e.g., ‘\w’ matches a literal ‘w’).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Because BWK `awk` supports them, the POSIX character classes (‘[[:alnum:]]’, etc.) are available.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] So too, interval expressions are allowed.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Characters described by octal and hexadecimal escape sequences are treated literally, even if they represent regexp metacharacters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This option remains for backwards compatibility but no longer has any real effect.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Case is normally significant in regular expressions, both when matching ordinary characters (i.e., not metacharacters) and inside bracket expressions.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Thus, a ‘w’ in a regular expression matches only a lowercase ‘w’ and not an uppercase ‘W’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The simplest way to do a case-independent match is to use a bracket expression—for example, ‘[Ww]’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] However, this can be cumbersome if you need to use it often, and it can make the regular expressions harder to read.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] There are two alternatives that you might prefer.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] One way to perform a case-insensitive match at a particular point in the program is to convert the data to a single case, using the `tolower()` or `toupper()` built-in string functions (which we haven’t discussed yet; see String-Manipulation Functions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] converts the first field to lowercase before matching against it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] This works in any POSIX-compliant `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Another method, specific to `gawk`, is to set the variable `IGNORECASE` to a nonzero value (see Predefined Variables).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] When `IGNORECASE` is not zero, *all* regexp and string operations ignore case.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Changing the value of `IGNORECASE` dynamically controls the case sensitivity of the program as it runs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In general, you cannot use `IGNORECASE` to make certain rules case insensitive and other rules case sensitive, as there is no straightforward way to set `IGNORECASE` just for the pattern of a particular rule.20 To do this, use either bracket expressions or `tolower()`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] However, one thing you can do with `IGNORECASE` only is dynamically turn case sensitivity on or off for all the rules at once.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] `IGNORECASE` can be set on the command line or in a `BEGIN` rule (see Other Command-Line Arguments; also see Startup and Cleanup Actions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Setting `IGNORECASE` from the command line is a way to make a program case insensitive without having to edit it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] In multibyte locales, the equivalences between upper- and lowercase characters are tested based on the wide-character values of the locale’s character set.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Prior to version 5.0, single-byte characters were tested based on the ISO-8859-1 (ISO Latin-1) character set.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] The value of `IGNORECASE` has no effect if `gawk` is in compatibility mode (see Command-Line Options).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Case is always significant in compatibility mode.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Release 5.4.0 of `gawk` introduced a new regular expression matching engine, named MinRX.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] MinRX is fully compliant with the POSIX standard for Extended Regular Expressions (EREs), including the additional features needed by `awk` and `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] It is also a little stricter that the original matchers are in terms of accepting valid regular expression syntax when specifying a regexp.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Previously, `gawk` used GNU `regex` and `dfa` from GNULIB.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] These matchers are fast and generally robust, albeit not fully POSIX compliant.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Because regular expression matching is such a fundamental part of what `awk` programs do, introducing a new regular expression engine has some risk associated with it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] To alleviate the risk, for the term of one major release, `gawk` continues to provide access to the original regexp matchers should that be needed.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] If the environment variable `GAWK_GNU_MATCHERS` exists, then `gawk` switches to using GNU `regex` and `dfa`, as previously.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Otherwise, the MinRX matcher is the default and that is what it uses.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Should you find a need to switch from MinRX to the original matchers, *please* submit a bug report describing what did not work (see Reporting Problems and Bugs).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] Doing so is very important, as it will help the maintainers and the MinRX author fix any issues that are found.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p04] After one major release, the old matchers, and the use of the `GAWK_GNU_MATCHERS` environment variable, will be removed from `gawk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In the typical `awk` program, `awk` reads all input either from the standard input (by default, this is the keyboard, but often it is a pipe from another command) or from files whose names you specify on the `awk` command line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If you specify input files, `awk` reads them in order, processing all the data from one before going on to the next.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The name of the current input file can be found in the predefined variable `FILENAME` (see Predefined Variables).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The input is read in units called *records*, and is processed by the rules of your program one record at a time.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Each record is automatically split into chunks called *fields*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This makes it more convenient for programs to work on the parts of a record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] On rare occasions, you may need to use the `getline` function.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The `getline` function is valuable both because it can do explicit input from any number of files, and because the files used with it do not have to be named on the `awk` command line (see Explicit Input with `getline`).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `awk` divides the input for your program into records and fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] It keeps track of the number of records that have been read so far from the current input file.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This value is stored in a predefined variable called `FNR`, which is reset to zero every time a new file is started.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Another predefined variable, `NR`, records the total number of input records read so far from all data files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] It starts at zero, but is never automatically reset to zero.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Normally, records are separated by newline characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] You can control how records are separated by assigning values to the built-in variable `RS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If `RS` is any single character, that character separates records.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Otherwise (in `gawk`), `RS` is treated as a regular expression.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This mechanism is explained in greater detail shortly.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Records are separated by a character called the *record separator*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] By default, the record separator is the newline character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This is why records are, by default, single lines.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] To use a different character for the record separator, simply assign that character to the predefined variable `RS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Like any other variable, the value of `RS` can be changed in the `awk` program with the assignment operator, ‘=’ (see Assignment Expressions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The new record-separator character should be enclosed in quotation marks, which indicate a string constant.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Often, the right time to do this is at the beginning of execution, before any input is processed, so that the very first record is read with the proper separator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] To do this, use the special `BEGIN` pattern (see The `BEGIN` and `END` Special Patterns).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] changes the value of `RS` to ‘u’, before reading any input.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The new value is a string whose first character is the letter “u”; as a result, records are separated by the letter “u”.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Then the input file is read, and the second rule in the `awk` program (the action with no pattern) prints each record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Because each `print` statement adds a newline at the end of its output, this `awk` program copies the input with each ‘u’ changed to a newline.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Note that the entry for the name ‘Bill’ is not split.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] It contains no ‘u’, so there is no reason to split the record, unlike the others, which each have one or more occurrences of the ‘u’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In fact, this record is treated as part of the previous record; the newline separating them in the output is the original newline in the data file, not the one added by `awk` when it printed the record!
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This sets `RS` to ‘u’ before processing mail-list.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Using an alphabetic character such as ‘u’ for the record separator is highly likely to produce strange results.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Using an unusual character such as ‘/’ is more likely to produce correct behavior in the majority of cases, but there are no guarantees.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `gawk` allows `RS` to be a full regular expression (discussed shortly; see Record Splitting with `gawk`).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Even so, using a regular expression metacharacter, such as ‘.’ as the single character in the value of `RS` has no special effect: it is treated literally.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This is required for backwards compatibility with both Unix `awk` and with POSIX.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Reaching the end of an input file terminates the current input record, even if the last character in the file is not the character in `RS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The empty string `""` (a string without any characters) has a special meaning as the value of `RS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] It means that records are separated by one or more blank lines and nothing else.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] See Multiple-Line Records for more details.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If you change the value of `RS` in the middle of an `awk` run, the new value is used to delimit subsequent records, but the record currently being processed, as well as records already processed, are not affected.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] After the end of the record has been determined, `gawk` sets the variable `RT` to the text in the input that matched `RS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] When using `gawk`, the value of `RS` is not limited to a one-character string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If it contains more than one character, it is treated as a regular expression (see Regular Expressions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] (c.e.) In general, each record ends at the next string that matches the regular expression; the next record starts at the end of the matching string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This general rule is actually at work in the usual case, where `RS` contains just a newline: a record ends at the beginning of the next matching string (the next newline in the input), and the following record starts just after the end of this string (at the first character of the following line).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The newline, because it matches `RS`, is not part of either record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] When `RS` is a single character, `RT` contains the same single character.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] However, when `RS` is a regular expression, `RT` contains the actual input text that matched the regular expression.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If the input file ends without any text matching `RS`, `gawk` sets `RT` to the null string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The following example illustrates both of these features.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The square brackets delineate the contents of `RT`, letting you see the leading and trailing whitespace.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] See A Simple Stream Editor for a more useful example of `RS` as a regexp and `RT`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `gawk` attempts to avoid this problem, but currently, there’s no guarantee that this will never happen.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The use of `RS` as a regular expression and the `RT` variable are `gawk` extensions; they are not available in compatibility mode (see Command-Line Options).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In compatibility mode, only the first character of the value of `RS` determines the end of the record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `mawk` has allowed `RS` to be a regexp for decades.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] As of October, 2019, BWK `awk` also supports it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] When `awk` reads an input record, the record is automatically *parsed* or separated by the `awk` utility into chunks called *fields*.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] By default, fields are separated by *whitespace*, like words in a line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Whitespace in `awk` means any string of one or more spaces, TABs, or newlines; other characters that are considered whitespace by other languages (such as formfeed, vertical tab, etc.) are *not* considered whitespace by `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The purpose of fields is to make it more convenient for you to refer to these pieces of the record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] You don’t have to use them—you can operate on the whole record if you want—but fields are what make simple `awk` programs so powerful.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] You use a dollar sign (‘$’) to refer to a field in an `awk` program, followed by the number of the field you want.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Thus, `$1` refers to the first field, `$2` to the second, and so on.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] (Unlike in the Unix shells, the field numbers are not limited to single digits.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Here the first field, or `$1`, is ‘This’, the second field, or `$2`, is ‘seems’, and so on.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Note that the last field, `$7`, is ‘example.’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Because there is no space between the ‘e’ and the ‘.’, the period is considered part of the seventh field.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `NF` is a predefined variable whose value is the number of fields in the current record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `awk` automatically updates the value of `NF` each time it reads a record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] No matter how many fields there are, the last field in a record can be represented by `$NF`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] So, `$NF` is the same as `$7`, which is ‘example.’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If you try to reference a field beyond the last one (such as `$8` when the record has only seven fields), you get the empty string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The use of `$0`, which looks like a reference to the “zeroth” field, is a special case: it represents the whole input record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Use it when you are not interested in specific fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This example prints each record in the file mail-list whose first field contains the string ‘li’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Any expression in the `awk` language can be used after a ‘$’ to refer to a field.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The value of the expression specifies the field number.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If the value is a string, rather than a number, it is converted to a number.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Recall that `NR` is the number of records read so far: one in the first record, two in the second, and so on.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] So this example prints the first field of the first record, the second field of the second record, and so on.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] For the twentieth record, field number 20 is printed; most likely, the record has fewer than 20 fields, so this prints a blank line.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `awk` evaluates the expression ‘(2*2)’ and uses its value as the number of the field to print.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The ‘*’ represents multiplication, so the expression ‘2*2’ evaluates to four.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The parentheses are used so that the multiplication is done before the ‘$’ operation; they are necessary whenever there is a binary operator24 in the field-number expression.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This example, then, prints the type of relationship (the fourth field) for every line of the file mail-list.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If the field number you compute is zero, you get the entire record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Similarly, string expressions that evaluate to zero also yield the entire record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Negative field numbers are not allowed; trying to reference one usually terminates the program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] (The POSIX standard does not define what happens when you reference a negative field number.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `gawk` notices this and terminates your program.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] As mentioned in Examining Fields, `awk` stores the current record’s number of fields in the built-in variable `NF` (also see Predefined Variables).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Thus, the expression `$NF` is not a special feature—it is the direct consequence of evaluating `NF` and using its value as a field number.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The contents of a field, as seen by `awk`, can be changed within an `awk` program; this changes what `awk` perceives as the current input record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The program first saves the original value of field three in the variable `nboxes`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The ‘-’ sign represents subtraction, so this program reassigns field three, `$3`, as the original value of field three minus ten: ‘$3 - 10’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] (See Arithmetic Operators.) Then it prints the original and new values for field three.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] For this to work, the text in `$3` must make sense as a number; the string of characters must be converted to a number for the computer to do arithmetic on it.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The number resulting from the subtraction is converted back to a string of characters that then becomes field three.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] When the value of a field is changed (as perceived by `awk`), the text of the input record is recalculated to contain the new field where the old one was.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In other words, `$0` changes to reflect the altered field.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] It is also possible to assign contents to fields that are out of range.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] For the file inventory-shipped, `$6` represents the total number of parcels shipped for a particular month.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Creating a new field changes `awk`’s internal copy of the current input record, which is the value of `$0`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Thus, if you do ‘print $0’ after adding a field, the record printed includes the new field, with the appropriate number of field separators between it and the previously existing fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This recomputation affects and is affected by `NF` (the number of fields; see Examining Fields).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] For example, the value of `NF` is set to the number of the highest field you create.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The exact format of `$0` is also affected by a feature that has not been discussed yet: the *output field separator*, `OFS`, used to separate the fields (see Output Separators).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Note, however, that merely *referencing* an out-of-range field does *not* change the value of either `$0` or `NF`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Referencing an out-of-range field only produces an empty string.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] should print ‘everything is normal’, because `NF+1` is certain to be out of range.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] (See The `if`-`else` Statement for more information about `awk`’s `if-else` statements.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] It is important to note that making an assignment to an existing field changes the value of `$0` but does not change the value of `NF`, even when you assign the empty string to a field.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The field is still there; it just has an empty value, delimited by the two colons between ‘a’ and ‘c’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The intervening field, `$5`, is created with an empty value (indicated by the second pair of adjacent colons), and `NF` is updated with the value six.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Decrementing `NF` throws away the values of the fields after the new value of `NF` and recomputes `$0`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Finally, there are times when it is convenient to force `awk` to rebuild the entire record, using the current values of the fields and `OFS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This forces `awk` to rebuild the record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] It does help to add a comment, as we’ve shown here.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] There is a flip side to the relationship between `$0` and the fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Any assignment to `$0` causes the record to be reparsed into fields using the *current* value of `FS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This also applies to any built-in function that updates `$0`, such as `sub()` and `gsub()` (see String-Manipulation Functions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The *field separator*, which is either a single character or a regular expression, controls the way `awk` splits an input record into fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `awk` scans the input record for character sequences that match the separator; the fields themselves are the text between the matches.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In the examples that follow, we use the bullet symbol (•) to represent spaces in the output.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] is split into three fields: ‘m’, ‘•g’, and ‘•gai•pan’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Note the leading spaces in the values of the second and third fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The field separator is represented by the predefined variable `FS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Shell programmers take note: `awk` does *not* use the name `IFS` that is used by the POSIX-compliant shells (such as the Unix Bourne shell, `sh`, or Bash).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The value of `FS` can be changed in the `awk` program with the assignment operator, ‘=’ (see Assignment Expressions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Often, the right time to do this is at the beginning of execution before any input has been processed, so that the very first record is read with the proper separator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] this `awk` program extracts and prints the string ‘•29•Oak•St.’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Sometimes the input data contains separator characters that don’t separate fields the way you thought they would.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The same program would extract ‘•LXIX’ instead of ‘•29•Oak•St.’.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If you were expecting the program to print the address, you would be surprised.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The moral is to choose your data layout and separator characters carefully to prevent such problems.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Fields are normally separated by whitespace sequences (spaces, TABs, and newlines), not by single spaces.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Two spaces in a row do not delimit an empty field.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The default value of the field separator `FS` is a string containing a single space, `" "`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If `awk` interpreted this value in the usual way, each space character would separate fields, so two spaces in a row would make an empty field between them.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The reason this does not happen is that a single space as the value of `FS` is a special case—it is taken to specify the default manner of delimiting fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If `FS` is any other single character, such as `","`, then each occurrence of that character separates two fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Two consecutive occurrences delimit an empty field.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] If the character occurs at the beginning or the end of the line, that too delimits an empty field.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The space character is the only single character that does not follow these rules.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The previous subsection discussed the use of single characters or simple strings as the value of `FS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] More generally, the value of `FS` may be a string containing any regular expression.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In this case, each match in the record for the regular expression separates fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] makes every area of an input line that consists of a comma followed by a space and a TAB into a field separator.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] For a less trivial example of a regular expression, try using single spaces to separate fields the way single commas are used.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] `FS` can be set to `"[ ]"` (left bracket, space, right bracket).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This regular expression matches a single space and nothing else (see Regular Expressions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] There is an important difference between the two cases of ‘FS = " "’ (a single space) and ‘FS = "[ \t\n]+"’ (a regular expression matching one or more spaces, TABs, or newlines).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] For both values of `FS`, fields are separated by *runs* (multiple adjacent occurrences) of spaces, TABs, and/or newlines.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] However, when the value of `FS` is `" "`, `awk` first strips leading and trailing whitespace from the record and then decides where the fields are.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In this case, the first field is null, or empty.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The stripping of leading and trailing whitespace also comes into play whenever `$0` is recomputed.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The first `print` statement prints the record as it was read, with leading whitespace intact.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The assignment to `$2` rebuilds `$0` by concatenating `$1` through `$NF` together, separated by the value of `OFS` (which is a space by default).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Because the leading whitespace was ignored when finding `$1`, it is not part of the new `$0`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Finally, the last `print` statement prints the new `$0`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] There is an additional subtlety to be aware of when using regular expressions for field splitting.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] It is not well specified in the POSIX standard, or anywhere else, what ‘^’ means when splitting fields.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Does the ‘^’ match only at the beginning of the entire record?
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Or is each field separator a new string?
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] It turns out that different `awk` versions answer this question differently, and you should not rely on any specific behavior in your programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] As a point of information, BWK `awk` allows ‘^’ to match only at the beginning of the record.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Finally, field splitting with regular expressions works differently than regexp matching with the `sub()`, `gsub()`, and `gensub()` (see String-Manipulation Functions).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Those functions allow a regexp to match the empty string; field splitting does not.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Thus, for example ‘FS = "()"’ does *not* split fields between characters.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] There are times when you may want to examine each character of a record separately.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This can be done in `gawk` by simply assigning the null string (`""`) to `FS`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] (c.e.) In this case, each individual character in the record becomes a separate field.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Traditionally, the behavior of `FS` equal to `""` was not defined.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In this case, most versions of Unix `awk` simply treat the entire record as only having one field.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] (d.c.) In compatibility mode (see Command-Line Options), if `FS` is the null string, then `gawk` also behaves this way.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Many commonly-used tools use a comma to separate fields, instead of whitespace.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] This is particularly true of popular spreadsheet programs.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] There is no universally accepted standard for the format of these files, although RFC 4180 lists the common practices.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] For decades, anyone wishing to work with CSV files and `awk` had to “roll their own” solution.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] (For an example, see Defining Fields by Content).
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In 2023, Brian Kernighan decided to add CSV support to his version of `awk`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In order to keep up, `gawk` too provides the same support as his version.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] To use CSV data, invoke `gawk` with either of the -k or --csv options.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Fields in CSV files are separated by commas.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In order to allow a comma to appear inside a field (i.e., as data), the field may be quoted by beginning and ending it with double quotes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In order to allow a double quote inside a field, the field *must* be quoted, and two double quotes represent an actual double quote.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The double quote that starts a quoted field must be the first character after the comma.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Additionally, and here’s where it gets messy, newlines are also allowed inside double-quoted fields!
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] In order to deal with such things, when processing CSV files, `gawk` scans the input data looking for newlines that are not enclosed in double quotes.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] Thus, use of the --csv option totally overrides normal record processing with `RS` (see How Input Is Split into Records), as well as field splitting with any of `FS`, `FIELDWIDTHS`, or `FPAT`.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] The behavior of the `split()` function (not formally discussed yet, see String-Manipulation Functions) differs slightly when processing CSV files.
[src:awk-lang/manual-gawk-p05] When called with two arguments (‘split(*string*, *array*)’), `split()` does CSV-based splitting.
